---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { site } from '../site.config';
import { withBase } from '../utils/base';

const focusAreas = [
  'Developer documentation and API references',
  'Docs-as-code and CI/CD pipelines',
  'AI agents for documentation automation',
  'Information architecture and content design',
  'Regulated documentation (ISO 13485) and process',
];
---

<BaseLayout
  title="About"
  description="About Pavlo Soletskyi — documentation engineer and senior technical writer."
>
  <div class="content content--with-sidebar">
    <article>
      <header class="page-intro">
        <h1>{site.title}</h1>
        <p class="tagline">
          Hi, I'm Pavlo — a documentation engineer and senior technical writer.
        </p>
      </header>

      <p>
        I own developer documentation end-to-end as a product — from getting-started guides,
        conceptual docs, and OpenAPI references through long-term maintenance. I also build the
        docs-as-code toolchain that keeps documentation accurate as product velocity scales:
        CI/CD-integrated pipelines, build-tool plugins that generate API contracts from source,
        and AI agents that produce references, architecture diagrams, and READMEs directly from
        microservice codebases.
      </p>

      <h2>How did you get into technical writing?</h2>
      <p>
        Like many technical writers, I didn't start in the field. I began in marketing and
        copywriting at EngSchool, where I produced content plans, commercial scripts, and blog
        posts. That work taught me how to write for an audience — but I wanted work that combined
        writing with something more structured and technical.
      </p>
      <p>
        I found that combination at GlobalLogic, where I spent nearly four years on regulated
        medical robotics documentation. I authored Design Specification Documents, System
        Requirement Specifications, validation plans, and test documentation to ISO 13485
        standards. I also led a cross-functional team of 14 software developers as project
        manager — sprint planning, risk assessment, client presentations, and compliance with
        QMS and SOPs.
      </p>
      <p>
        Along the way I took on part-time technical writing at Mate Academy, creating and
        editing educational content for Python, Java, JavaScript, DevOps, and QA courses in
        Ukrainian and English. I built a unified style guide and streamlined the review process
        — my first real docs-as-code experience with Markdown and Git.
      </p>
      <p>
        In 2025 I moved into senior documentation engineering at GridDynamics, where I design
        and maintain the automated documentation infrastructure for a large microservices platform.
        To my surprise (and relief), I found that documentation engineering combines everything
        I care about: clear writing, software tooling, and making developers' lives easier.
      </p>

      <h2>What do you work on today?</h2>
      <p>
        My main project is an AI-driven docs-as-code pipeline integrated into CI/CD. On every
        build across roughly 120 microservices, the pipeline regenerates developer documentation
        so references stay in sync with the codebase and manual drift doesn't accumulate.
      </p>
      <p>
        A custom Gradle plugin (Groovy plugin layer, core logic in Java) auto-generates OpenAPI
        contracts from annotated Java code — removing manual API-contract authoring across 85 REST
        services. Five autonomous AI-agent capabilities power the rest of the pipeline: per-service
        README generation, service- and system-level architecture diagramming, automated publishing
        to the internal developer portal, business-requirements extraction from REST controller
        logic, and AGENT.md authoring to standardize how AI coding agents interpret the codebase.
      </p>
      <p>
        Reliability matters as much as generation. I engineered guardrails for concurrency on
        parallel writes, a three-layer loop-prevention strategy, and token-quota controls so
        automated documentation is safe to run on every CI execution without recurring defects.
      </p>

      <h2>What's your educational background?</h2>
      <p>
        I earned a B.A. in Applied Linguistics from Lviv Polytechnic University in 2024. Before
        that, I completed a summer educational program at Diablo Valley College in California
        (2021).
      </p>
      <p>
        The linguistics background carries over directly to my work. Applied linguistics is
        essentially the study of how language functions in real contexts — which is what
        information architecture and technical content design are about. I think about reader
        mental models, terminology consistency, and how structure affects comprehension the
        same way a linguist thinks about syntax and pragmatics.
      </p>

      <h2>Leadership and community</h2>
      <p>
        At GlobalLogic I led a team of 14 developers through the full project lifecycle — not
        just writing docs but translating client needs into structured work, defending proposals,
        and keeping everyone aligned with ISO 13485 requirements.
      </p>
      <p>
        Outside of work, I served as project manager for Pobachymos Foundation (May 2023 – March
        2024), organizing charity auctions across Ukraine.
      </p>
      <p>
        I speak English (full professional proficiency), Ukrainian (native), and German (limited
        working proficiency).
      </p>

      <h2>What topics do you care about?</h2>
      <p>On this site I write about topics such as the following:</p>
      <ul class="focus-list">
        {focusAreas.map((area) => (
          <li>{area}</li>
        ))}
      </ul>

      <h2>How can you reach me?</h2>
      <p>
        If you have a question or want to discuss documentation engineering, you can
        <a href={withBase('contact/')}>contact me here</a> or email me at
        <a href={`mailto:${site.email}`}>{site.email}</a>.
      </p>
    </article>

    <aside class="sidebar" aria-label="Focus areas">
      <h3>Focus areas</h3>
      <ul>
        {focusAreas.map((area) => (
          <li>{area}</li>
        ))}
      </ul>
    </aside>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
